John Edward: Language skills are a necessity for global citizens
Scottish independent schools have had a number of academic successes and this continues in 2018 with other excellent exam results. Individual and group successes in sports, art, music and other community activities only underline this.
These schools have more than 30,000 pupils across Scotland, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) and aim to provide their pupils and parents with the best possible level of service.
Independent schools prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As a sector of education that can design and implement individualized school curricula, we see that modern languages are still popular and in demand in schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a person in a language he understands, it goes straight to his head.
If you speak to him in his own language, it goes straight to his heart.”
It is an important observation that if we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries, we cannot rely only on English.
The latest results of this year’s exams show that languages come first in the tables, with independent schools having the highest success rate.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned a foreign language achieved the best grade of A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools show that 72 per cent of Mandarin students, 72 per cent of German students, 69 per cent of French students and 63 per cent of Spanish students achieved the highest A grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as important skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Languages as subjects chosen by pupils are as important as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the study plans of independent and other schools.
A 2014 survey by the UK’s Employment and Skills Commission found that 17 percent of job vacancies are due to reasons employers cite as vacancy problems.
Therefore, language skills are increasingly becoming a necessity in preparing young people for their future careers.
As more and more jobs require languages, these skills are a necessity in a globalised world.
Whatever career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have a real advantage in the future that he has such a lifelong skill.
Thanks to the ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries, a person who speaks multiple languages automatically gains an advantage over the competition.
According to a survey conducted by YouGov in 2013 among 4,000 adults in the UK, 75 percent of them could not speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, with the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage of people, namely 15 percent, was French.
Therefore, it is important for today’s children to invest in language learning.
If children know more languages, especially the languages of emerging economies, they will be more likely to find meaningful employment.
In Scotland, each school differs in what languages it teaches.
A number of schools focus on more classical modern languages, while others teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK in view of 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what the child is interested in, he will always have a choice of several languages at independent schools with teachers who are experts in the field.
Scottish Independent Schools are dedicated to providing an educational environment that prepares children and equips them with the skills they need to succeed, whatever the future holds.
At this point, it cannot be denied that languages are essential for the future of the country in the global business environment, so this must be reflected in education.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and landmark to young people in Scotland.
Il faut bien le faire.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
