"But we don't see a corresponding response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no trust in our national security, and under such circumstances, it is impossible to disarm unilaterally.”
While Ri repeated known North Korean complaints about Washington’s opposition to a “gradual” approach to denuclearization that would reward North Korea for every step it took, his statement seemed significant in not rejecting unilateral denuclearization just because Pyongyang had gone through it in the past.
Ri mentioned the joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at the first summit between the US president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work to “denuclearize the Korean peninsula” while Trump pledged guarantees of North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking a formal end to the 1950-53 war, but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls for tough international sanctions against North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on ‘denuclearization first’ and increases pressure on sanctions to enforce its goals, and even opposes ‘declaring an end to the war’,” Ri said.
“The impression that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream of people who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the ongoing sanctions deepen our mistrust.”
Ri did not mention the plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, which the US leader stressed at the UN earlier in the week.
Instead, the minister stressed three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months, adding: “If South Korea and not the US were on the side of the denuclearization issue, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a stalemate.”
However, Ri’s tone was dramatically different from last year’s one when he told the UN General Assembly that North Korea’s missile targeting on U.S. soil was inevitable after Trump’s “Mr. Evil President” labeled Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
At the United Nations this year, Trump, who last year threatened to “totally destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage to take steps to disarm, but said much work still had to be done and sanctions must remain in place until North Korea was completely denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he didn’t have a timeframe for that, saying, “If it takes two years, three years, or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
