Harvard students take a course to teach them enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has led all of its students to sleep more, in an effort to fight the growing culture of macho studios all night long, where students don’t sleep and are encouraged with caffeine.
Academics have found that students at the world’s most renowned university are often helpless when it comes to taking care of themselves.
The course was designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start the course after he lectured on the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are you telling me this now, in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep — which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
The course, which was first introduced this year, explains to students basic information about how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance and improve their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of health services at the university, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students were really seriously sleepy during the week.
The hour-long course includes a number of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is a picture of student dormitories where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep and the importance of proper sleeping habits.
In another section, participants are informed about how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
The campus map with interactive icons then invites participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that the behavior of students will not change immediately.
However, we believe they have the right to know – just as you have the right to know the health effects of smoking cigarettes,” Czeisler added.
A culture of pride in “all night studying” still exists, he added, adding that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean that the problem of sleep deprivation is also growing.
Sufficient sleep of good quality should be the student's "secret weapon" to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said - even to avoid gaining weight, because sleep deprivation switches the brain to starvation mode, so the person is still hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California student of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler design a course that one of his classes attended last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course opened his eyes and inspired him to push the whole course.
He hopes that the next step will be to ask all graduate students to complete a similar degree program before entering a competitive institution.
The professor advised students to consider setting the alarm at the time when to go to bed, as well as when to wake up, and be aware of the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt your circadian rhythm, leading to problems with falling asleep.
