The National Trust is listening to the secret life of bats.
New research is underway at the bat habitat in the Scottish Highlands to uncover how bats use the landscape to hunt for food.
There is hope that the research findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and help guide future activities to preserve this species.
The study, which is being carried out by scientists from the National Trust for Scotland Association, will track bats of whistles and the smallest and brownest long-tailed and aquatic bats at the Inverewe Gardens Botanical Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key areas in this bat habitat, which will monitor the activities of bats throughout the season.
NHS employees and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using handheld detectors.
