Subsequently, a habitat map and a report will be released, which will create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, NTS Natural Resources Conservation Advisor, hopes the results will show which habitat areas are most important for bats and how each species uses them.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as meadow formation, and best practice in maintaining forested areas for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the whole of Great Britain has been declining significantly in the last century.
They are endangered as a result of construction and territorial development that affect colonies and the natural environment.
Wind turbines and lighting, as well as fly traps and chemical treatment of building materials and cat attacks can also pose a risk.
