Red tide update: Concentrations decrease in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota districts
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission points to an overall decline in red tide concentrations in the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, spots of flowering water are now reported from the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier – this indicates a decreasing concentration.
The blooming water of the Red Tide has a range of about 130 miles of coastline from the northern Pinellas County to the southern Lee County.
The spots were spotted about 10 miles off the coast in Hillsborough County, but last week there were relatively fewer spots.
The red tide was also observed in the Pasco district.
Low to high concentrations were observed in the county of Hillsborough, the lowest to high concentrations in the county of Manatee, the lowest to high concentrations in the county of Sarasota, the lowest to medium concentrations in the county of Charlotte, and the lowest to high concentrations in the county of Charlotte.
Respiratory irritations continue to occur in the districts of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
Airway irritation was not reported in northwest Florida last week.
